>
	<h1>About</h1>

	<p>
		I'm an emergency medicine clinician in East London. I also build clinical AI products.
	</p>

	<p>
		The two things are connected — everything I've built started as a problem I saw on shift.
	</p>

	<h2>The work</h2>

	<p>
		I trained as a doctor in India, graduating from Kasturba Medical College in Manipal in 2019. I joined the medical operations and product team at DailyRounds in Bengaluru, where I spent two and a half years helping scale India's leading medical education platform from an early-stage startup to over half a million users. I led a cross-functional team of twenty medical editors, designed the flagship "Pearls" feature, and did the unglamorous day-to-day work of translating clinical workflow into product requirements.
	</p>

	<p>
		Between 2022 and 2023 I ran a small family practice in Kerala. It was paper-based when I arrived. I partnered with a fintech-backed EHR startup to install and configure a digital record system; within weeks the clinic was running on software that our staff actively preferred to the old ledgers. That experience — being the only person in a resource-limited clinic who understood both the medicine and the technology — shaped how I think about health-tech deployment.
	</p>

	<p>
		I moved to London in late 2023 to practise emergency medicine at Whipps Cross Hospital as part of Barts Health NHS Trust. I'm currently an ST3-equivalent trust-grade doctor in a busy adult A&E, covering the full range of undifferentiated presentations across resus, majors, and ambulatory care. I co-lead a departmental quality improvement project on mental health pathway compliance and I teach medical students and foundation doctors on shift.
	</p>

	<h2>The building</h2>

	<p>
		Alongside clinical work, I build things. Most of them clinical AI.
	</p>

	<p>
		I've been experimenting with machine learning for healthcare since 2018, when I trained a convolutional neural network in PyTorch to prioritise chest X-rays as a final-year student. In 2020 I placed second at the MIT COVID-19 Hackathon with a team building AI triage tools. In 2022 I launched NeurallyMed — an AI-powered PLAB exam preparation platform — which was acquired in 2023.
	</p>

	<p>
		I'm a founding engineer at two sister ventures, <strong>Peerr.io</strong> and <strong>Aiigent.io</strong>, working on secure, AI-powered tooling for clinical networking and workflow. On the side I build smaller things I need — an AI guidelines retrieval platform for the ED (<strong>Aide</strong>), a fitness and nutrition assistant for myself (<strong>Leanifi</strong>), a project microsite for the QIP I'm running at Whipps (<strong>qip.fazeen.dev</strong>). Some of these turn into products. Some stay personal tools. All of them start with a problem I saw on a shift.
	</p>

	<h2>What I care about</h2>

	<p>
		Most clinical AI projects fail not because the model is weak but because the implementation is weak. Poor workflow integration, weak governance, unclear accountability, thin evaluation. I want to do the opposite — ship things, evaluate them properly, write down what worked and what didn't so other people don't have to learn the same lessons from scratch.
	</p>

	<p>That's the thread.</p>

	<hr />

	<p>
		Available for collaborations in clinical AI deployment, digital health product consulting, and speaking on clinician-led technology development. <a href="/contact">Contact me</a>.
	</p>
</ProseLayout>
